name: KOI-680 b
description: This planet was discovered with the Kepler telescope and confirmed with the SOPHIE spectrograph in France.

name: KOI-806.03
description: This planet candidate was discovered with the Kepler spacecraft. Because there are multiple phenomena that can create a signal that looks similar to a planetary transit, the candidates have to be confirmed with another method. For Kepler-30 the planetary nature of the companions has been confirmed by transit timing variations, caused by other planets in the system, and a stability analysis.

name: KOI-806.02
description: This planet candidate was discovered with the Kepler spacecraft. Its host star gets periodically fainter whenever the planet is in front of the star. Because there are multiple phenomena that can create a signal that looks similar to a planetary transit, the candidates have to be confirmed with another method. For Kepler-30 the planetary nature of the companions has been confirmed by transit timing variations, caused by other planets in the system, and a stability analysis.

name: KOI-806.01
description: This planet candidate was discovered with the Kepler spacecraft. Because there are multiple phenomena that can create a signal that looks similar to a planetary transit, the candidates have to be confirmed with another method. For Kepler-30 the planetary nature of the companions has been confirmed by transit timing variations, caused by other planets in the system, and a stability analysis.

name: KOI-830 b
description: This planet had been flagged by the Kepler Team as a planet candidate. Follow-up observations using the HARPS-N spectrograph at the Telescopio Nazionale Galileo have now confirmed its planetary nature.

name: KOI-89 b
description: KOI-89.01 orbits a rapidly-rotating, oblate star. The planet's orbit has a sky-projected misalignment of -32° with respect to the stellar equator, while the derived true orbital obliquity is 72°.

name: KOI-89.02
description: KOI-89.02 orbits a rapidly-rotating, oblate star. The planet's orbit has a sky-projected misalignment of -32° with respect to the stellar equator, while the derived true orbital obliquity is 73°.

name: Lalande 21185 b
description: Data for this planet was imported from the exoplanet.eu database.

name: LHS 1140 b
description: LHS 1140 b is a rocky super-Earth located in the potential liquid water zone of its star.

name: LkCa 15 c
description: The young (2 Myr) solar analog LkCa 15 shows evidence for a (proto)planet surrounded by dusty material. The object is located in a known gap in the transitional disk. More planets might be present in this system.

name: Lupus-TR 3b
description: Lupus-TR 3b is the only planet in the system. The planet is a typical a hot Jupiter orbiting Lupus-TR 3, an early dwarf type star

name: MOA-2007-BLG-192L b
description: The exoplanet MOA-2007-BLG-192L b is a super-Earth or sub-Neptune orbiting a low-mass red dwarf star.

name: MOA-2007-BLG-400L b
description: MOA-2007-BLG-400Lb is a jovian planet on a wide orbit around a low-mass star. An alternative solution to the microlensing data gives a semimajor axis of 0.72 AU.

name: MOA 2008-BLG-310L b
description: MOA-2008-BLG-310Lb is a super-Neptune orbiting a low-mass star. An earlier claimed detection of light from the host star was shown to be incorrect by Bhattacharya et al. (2017).

name: MOA-2008-BLG-379L b
description: MOA-2008-BLG-379Lb is a planetary mass object discovered by gravitational microlensing. Because a faint source star crossed a large resonant caustic, the planetary signal dominates the light curve. A statistical model has been used to determine the physical system parameters.

name: MOA-2010-BLG-073L b
description: The planet MOA-2010-BLG-073L b was discovered by the Microlensing Observations in Astrophysics (MOA) survey. In a microlensing event like this, the light from a source star is bent and magnified by a foreground star and a planet. In this case the source star was previously known to be photometrically variable.

name: MOA-2010-BLG-117L b
description: MOA-2010-BLG-117 was a microlensing event with a binary source star. The lens system contains a gas giant orbiting a low-mass star.

name: MOA-2010-BLG-311 b
description: This object was observed in a gravitational microlensing event. A good mass estimate could not be obtained although the object is most likely of planetary nature. Unfortunately microlensing events are not repeatable and the planet is therefore marked as controversial. The lens may be a member of the globular cluster NGC 6553.

name: MOA-2010-BLG-328L b
description: MOA-2010-BLG-328 is a planetary microlensing event. Multiple fits (including one with source orbital motion, xallarap) can explain the system. The mass of the companion might therefore change. However, all fits clearly show the presence of a planery mass object: MOA-2010-BLG-328L b.

name: MOA-2010-BLG-353L b
description: MOA-2010-BLG-353Lb is a Saturn-mass planet orbiting a low-mass star. It was discovered in archived light curve data for a microlensing event that occurred in 2010.

name: MOA-2010-BLG-477L b
description: Densely covered observations of a high-magnification event led to the discovery of the planet MOA-2010-BLG-477 b. Many different telescopes around the world have been used in this collaborative effort, including a 40cm telescope in Antartica.

name: MOA-2011-BLG-028L b
description: MOA-2011-BLG-028Lb is a Neptune-mass planet orbiting a star in the galactic bulge.

name: MOA-2011-BLG-262Lb
description: The microlensing event MOA-2011-BLG-262 allows for two possible interpretations of the lens system: either it is a relatively nearby free-floating 3.6 Jupiter masses object with a 0.54 Earth mass satellite, or it is a low-mass star in the galactic bulge with a Neptune-class planet. The values given here are for the latter scenario.

name: MOA-2011-BLG-293L b
description: MOA-2011-BLG-293L b is a planet discovered by gravitational microlensing. Using follow-up observations on Keck, astronomers have identified the planet to lie in or near the habitable zone. It could in principle have habitable moons. It is also the first planet to be identified as being in the Galactic bulge with good confidence.

name: MOA 2011-BLG-322L b
description: MOA-2011-BLG-322L b is a giant planet which was discovered by MOA, OGLE and the Wise Observatory. These observatories form a network and conduct a second generation microlensing survey. The survey aims to discover and characterize extrasolar planets and their frequency, by means of round-the-clock high-cadence monitoring of a large area of the Galactic bulge.

name: MOA-2012-BLG-006L b
description: MOA-2012-BLG-006Lb is an object near the dividing line between planets and brown dwarfs.

name: MOA-2013-BLG-220L b
description: MOA-2013-BLG-220L is a microlensing event observed in 2013. The lens system has a mass ratio of 0.003 but the distance and mass are not well constrained, so the system could range from a Saturn-mass planet orbiting a brown dwarf to a super-Jupiter orbiting a K-dwarf.

name: MOA-2013-BLG-605L b
description: Because of degeneracies involved in modelling the microlensing event MOA-2013-BLG-605, there are three possible models for the lens system. In the first, a 21 Earth-mass planet orbits a 0.19 solar mass star at a distance of 4.2 AU. This would make the planet a Neptune-analogue. In the second, a 7.9 Earth-mass planet orbits a 71 Jupiter-mass brown dwarf at 2.1 AU, and in the third a 3.2 Earth-mass planet orbits a 26 Jupiter-mass brown dwarf at 0.94 AU. Future observations taken when the lens system has moved sufficiently far away from the source star will be able to determine whether the stellar model is the correct one.

name: MOA-2016-BLG-227L b
description: MOA-2016-BLG-227Lb is a massive planet orbiting a low-mass star.

name: MOA-bin-1L b
description: This planet has been discovered in data from the 2006-2007 MOA project by Bennett et al (2012). It is the first planetary event in which the stellar host is only detected through binary microlensing events.

name: mu Leo b
description: The planet mu Leo b is orbiting the K giant mu Leonis, also known as Rasalas (the northern star of the lion's head). It was found using data from the Bohyunsan Observatory.

name: NGC 2423 3 b
description: NGC 2423 MMU 3 b is a massive giant planet or brown dwarf orbiting a giant star in the open cluster NGC 2423.

name: NGC 4349 No 127 b
description: NGC 4349 MMU 127 b is a super-Jovian or brown dwarf orbiting a giant star in the open cluster NGC 4349.

name: NGTS-1 b
description: This Hot Jupiter transiting an early M-dwarf was the first discovery of Next Generation Transit Survey (NGTS).

name: NN Ser (AB) c
description: NN Ser AB is a short-period eclipsing binary. The system hosts a white dwarf, a red dwarf and two planets.

name: NN Ser (AB) d
description: NN Ser AB is a short-period eclipsing binary. The system hosts a white dwarf, a red dwarf and two planets.

name: NSVS 14256825 c
description: NSVS 14256825 is an HW Vir type binary which consists of a hot subdwarf and a main-sequence low-mass star in a close orbit.

name: NSVS 14256825 d
description: NSVS 14256825 is an HW Vir type binary which consists of a hot subdwarf and a main-sequence low-mass star in a close orbit.

name: Nu Oct A b
description: Periodic radial velocity variations in the giant star Nu Octantis indicate the possible presence of a planet. In order to remain stable within the Nu Octantis binary system, the planet must be on a retrograde orbit.

name: nu Oph b
description: The Nu Ophiuchi system contains a pair of massive planets or brown dwarfs close to a 6:1 resonance.

name: nu Oph c
description: The Nu Ophiuchi system contains a pair of massive planets or brown dwarfs close to a 6:1 resonance.

name: NY Virginis (AB) b
description: The rapidly pulsating eclipsing binary NY Virginis has a period of 0.1 days. On a much longer timescale of 7.9 years, the system exhibits small amplitude cyclic variations which are associated with a third body in the system. A recent paper by Qian et. al. claims that this body is a giant circumbinary planet orbiting NY Vir at a distance of 3.3 astronomical units. There might be another planet in this system with an even longer orbital period, probably more than 15 years.

name: OGLE-2003-BLG-235L b
description: OGLE-2003-BLG-235/MOA-2003-BLG-53 was the first microlensing event to result in a definitive planet detection. The host star was detected by Bennett et al. (2006) who discovered that it is a K-dwarf.

name: OGLE-2005-BLG-71L b
description: OGLE 2005-BLG-71L b is a massive giant planet orbiting a red dwarf star.

name: OGLE-2005-BLG-169L b
description: The planetary signal in the microlensing event OGLE-2005-BLG-169 was confirmed in 2015 with follow-up measurements of the relative proper motion of the source and lens stars. The lens system consists of a 14.1 Earth mass planet orbiting a 0.69 solar mass K-dwarf with a projected separation of 3.5 AU. Assuming random orientation of the system, the 3D separation is 4.0+2.2-0.6 AU, locating it well beyond the star's snowline. The planet likely represents a "failed Jupiter core".

name: OGLE-2005-BLG-390L b
description: OGLE-2005-BLG-390L b is a cold super-Earth or sub-Neptune planet orbiting a low-mass star.

name: OGLE-2006-BLG-109L b
description: OGLE-2006-BLG-109L is a two-planet system discovered by microlensing. The system resembles a scaled-down version of Jupiter and Saturn.

name: OGLE-2006-BLG-109L c
description: OGLE-2006-BLG-109L is a two-planet system discovered by microlensing. The system resembles a scaled-down version of Jupiter and Saturn.

name: OGLE-2007-BLG-349L (AB) c
description: The Saturn-mass planet OGLE-2007-BLG-349L(AB)c is the first circumbinary planet detected by microlensing.

name: OGLE-2008-BLG-092L A b
description: The planet OGLE-2008-BLG-092LAb is a planet with 3.3 times the mass of Neptune in a binary stellar system. The discovery was made using the gravitational microlensing method. Some of the physical parameters of the system are not well constrained and model dependent.

name: OGLE-2011-BLG-251L b
description: The planet OGLE-2011-BLG-0251L b was discovered using gravitational microlensing. The host star is an M dwarf. It is located towards the Galactic Bulge. The planet lies beyond the snow-line, an important clue for planet formation models.

name: OGLE-2011-BLG-0265L b
description: A cold Jupiter orbits an M-dwarf star that gave rise to the microlensing event OGLE-2011-BLG-0265. The preferred solution out of two host star/planet configurations is presented here.

name: OGLE-2012-BLG-0026L b
description: This multi-planetary system was discovered during a high-magnification gravitational microlensing event. Both planets are located beyond the snow-line, an important clue for planet formation models. Adaptive optics imaging was used to detect the flux from the host star.

name: OGLE-2012-BLG-0026L c
description: This multi-planetary system was discovered during a high-magnification gravitational microlensing event. Both planets are located beyond the snow-line, an important clue for planet formation models. Adaptive optics imaging was used to detect the flux from the host star.

name: OGLE-2012-BLG-0358L b
description: OGLE-2012-BLG-0358L b is a planetary mass object which is orbiting a brown dwarf. The discovery of this system suggests that planets can form around brown dwarf hosts, probably in a protoplanetary disk analogous to those around main sequence stars.

name: OGLE-2012-BLG-0406L b
description: This planetary system was discovered during a high-magnification gravitational microlensing event. It is the first microlensing planet found by analyzing data from only a single telescope. The planet is located beyond the snow-line. Some core accretion theories favor the formation of massive planets inside the snow-line. However, planetary migration in the protoplanetary disk might explain why the planet has moved outwards.

name: OGLE-2015-BLG-0563L b
description: OGLE-2015-BLG-0563Lb is a Saturn-mass planet orbiting a low-mass dwarf star. The wide model for the lens system gives an alternate value for the projected separation of 4.2+1.5/-2.5 AU.

name: OGLE-2012-BLG-0724L b
description: OGLE-2012-BLG-0724Lb is a Saturn-mass planet orbiting an M dwarf. The original analysis of the microlensing event identified the system as a stellar binary.

name: OGLE-2012-BLG-0950L b
description: OGLE-2012-BLG-0950Lb was the first planet with a mass measurement from only microlens parallax and lens flux.

name: OGLE-2013-BLG-0102L B
description: OGLE-2013-BLG-0102 was a microlensing event observed towards the galactic bulge. The lens system is a low-mass binary consisting of a primary at the hydrogen-burning limit and a secondary at the deuterium-burning limit. Depending on the definitions used, the secondary may either be regarded as a giant planet or a low-mass brown dwarf.

name: OGLE-2013-BLG-0132L b
description: OGLE-2013-BLG-0132Lb is a Saturn-mass planet orbiting a low-mass star.

name: OGLE-2013-BLG-0341L B b
description: The planet OGLE-20130BLG-0341LB b was discovered with the gravitational microlensing method. The planet is orbiting a star with a very low luminosity. That is why even though the planet's semimajor axis is smaller than that of Earth, its temperature is well below freezing.

name: OGLE-2013-BLG-0723L B b
description: OGLE-2013-BLG-0723LBb was announced as a Venus-mass planet orbiting a brown dwarf of 32 Jupiter masses, which is itself orbiting a low-mass star. It would therefore be considered either a scaled-up exommon system or a scaled-down planetary system. Han et al. (2016) showed that the light curve could be better modelled as a binary consisting of 0.2 and 0.1 solar mass stars without a planet.

name: OGLE-2013-BLG-1721L b
description: OGLE-2013-BLG-1721Lb is a Saturn-mass planet orbiting a low-mass star.

name: OGLE-2013-BLG-1761L b
description: OGLE-2013-BLG-1761Lb is a jovian planet orbiting an M or K dwarf star which is likely to be located in the Galactic bulge.

name: OGLE-2014-BLG-0124L b
description: The microlens parallax of the microlensing event OGLE-2014-BLG-0124 was measured using data from the Spitzer Space Telescope.

name: OGLE-2014-BLG-0676L b
description: OGLE-2014-BLG-0676L is a cold gas-giant planet orbiting a 0.62 solar mass star.

name: OGLE-2014-BLG-1722L b
description: OGLE-2014-BLG-1722L is a two-planet system detected by gravitational microlensing.

name: OGLE-2014-BLG-1722L c
description: OGLE-2014-BLG-1722L is a two-planet system detected by gravitational microlensing.

name: OGLE-2014-BLG-1760L b
description: OGLE-2014-BLG-1760Lb is a cold giant planet orbiting a star located in or near the galactic bulge.

name: OGLE-2015-BLG-0051L b
description: OGLE-2015-BLG-0051Lb/KMT-2015-BLG-0048Lb is a giant planet orbiting a low-mass star in the Galactic bulge.

name: OGLE-2015-BLG-0954L b
description: The planet OGLE-2015-BLG-0954Lb is a massive planet orbiting an M-dwarf host star. The source crossing time of the microlensing event was 16 minutes.

name: OGLE-2015-BLG-0966L b
description: OGLE-2015-BLG-0966Lb is a cold Neptune-like planet orbiting a star in the galactic disc. It is not known whether the source star of the microlensing event is located in the galactic bulge or the galactic disc, which affects the estimate of the distance and separation of the lens system. The values given here are for the case where the source is located in the bulge.

name: OGLE-2016-BLG-0263L b
description: OGLE-2016-BLG-0263Lb is a massive planet orbiting a star near the bottom of the main sequence.

name: OGLE-2016-BLG-0613L AB b
description: Several possible models exist for the OGLE-2016-BLG-0613L system, including the possibility that the secondary star is a brown dwarf and where the planet is in an S-type orbit around the primary star.

name: OGLE-2016-BLG-1190L b
description: OGLE-2016-BLG-1190Lb is an object at the boundary between planets and brown dwarfs. The system lies in the Galactic bulge.

name: OGLE-2016-BLG-1195L b
description: OGLE-2016-BLG-1195L b is an Earth-mass planet orbiting an ultracool dwarf star.

name: OGLE-2017-BLG-0173L b
description: OGLE-2017-BLG-0173Lb was discovered in a "Hollywood" microlensing event. Alternative models result in planetary masses around 8 Earth masses.

name: OGLE-2017-BLG-0373L b
description: OGLE-2017-BLG-0373Lb is a giant planet orbiting a red dwarf star.

name: OGLE-2017-BLG-0482L b
description: OGLE-2017-BLG-0482Lb is a Uranus-mass planet orbiting a low-mass star.

name: OGLE-2017-BLG-1140L b
description: OGLE-2017-BLG-1140Lb is a giant planet orbiting at approximately 1 AU from a red dwarf star.

name: OGLE-2017-BLG-1434L b
description: OGLE-2017-BLG-1434Lb is a cold super-Earth or sub-Neptune planet orbiting a red dwarf star.

name: OGLE-2017-BLG-1522L b
description: OGLE-2017-BLG-1522Lb is a gas giant orbiting a brown dwarf in the Galactic bulge.

name: OGLE-TR-113 b
description: OGLE-TR-113b is a hot Jupiter orbiting a K-type star.

name: Omega Serpentis b
description: The exoplanet Omega Serpentis b is orbiting a star in the northern constellation Serpens. It was discovered using the radial velocity method. The measurements were taken at the Okaya Astrophysical Observatory.

name: omi CrB b
description: Discovered with precise Doppler measurements at Okayama Astrophysical Observatory.

name: omi UMa b
description: Discovered with precise Doppler measurements at Okayama Astrophysical Observatory.

name: PH-1 A(ab) b
description: PH 1 b is a circumbinary planet in a quadruple star system. It is orbiting a double star and there is a second pair of stars at approximately 1000 AU. Citizen scientists discovered this planet by looking at many light curves using the online tool at planethunters.org.

name: PH-2 b
description: The exoplanet PH-2 b was discovered by citizen scientists using an online tool at planethunters.org. The planet is a gas giant and could be located in the star's habitable zone. The system might also have a faint binary companion.

name: POTS-1 b
description: POTS-1 b is a Hot Jupiter and the first planet discovered by the pre-OmegaTranS project survey. This survey is looking at the Carina region of the Galactic disc with the European Southern Observatory Wide Field Imager at La Silla Observatory.

name: Pr0201 b
description: This planet is a so-called Hot Jupiter which orbits tightly around its parent star in the Beehive Cluster, a collection of roughly 1,000 stars that appear to be swarming around a common center. The planet is not habitable but its sky would be starrier than what we see from Earth.

name: Pr0211 b
description: This planet is a so-called Hot Jupiter which orbits tightly around its parent star in the Beehive Cluster, a collection of roughly 1,000 stars that appear to be swarming around a common center. The planet is not habitable but its sky would be starrier than what we see from Earth.

name: Pr0211 c
description: Pr0211 c is a super-Jovian planet in a highly-elliptical orbit. The discovery of this planet was the first time a multiplanet system had been observed in an open cluster.

name: Psi-1 Draconis B b
description: Psi-1 Draconis is a triple star system containing the spectroscopic binary Psi-1 Draconis AC, and their distant companion Psi-1 Draconis B. The radial velocities of Psi-1 Draconis B indicate the presence of a jovian planet on an eccentric, long-period orbit and a trend indicating the presence of an additional companion. The trend is not compatible with being caused by Psi-1 Draconis AC, so indicates the presence of an additional, likely substellar object outside the orbit of the known jovian planet.

name: PSO J318.5-22
description: PSO J318-22 is a free floating planetary mass object. It was discovered using the Pan-STARRS1 survey and is part of the beta Pictoris moving group. Evolutionary models give the object a temperature of 1160K and a mass about 6 times that of Jupiter, making PSO J318-22 one of the lowest mass free-floating objects in the solar neighborhood.

name: PSR B1620-26 b
description: PSR B1620-26 b is a circum-binary planet. It is orbiting a pulsar and a white dwarf in the globular cluster M4. The cluster is estimated to be 12.2 billion years old.

name: PSR J1719-1438 b
description: The 5.7ms pulsar PSR J1719-14 shows timing variations on a 2.17 hour timescale. These can be explained with a Jovian planet. However, because of the planet's short distance to the star, its density has to be more then 20 times that of Jupiter. The planet is most likely a remnant of a binary star which avoided complete destruction. The chemical composition, pressure and dimensions of the planet indicate that it is crystallized, or in other words, a very big diamond (Bailes et al 2011).

name: PTFO 8-8695 b
description: PTFO 8-8695 b is a Jupiter-sized candidate planet orbiting a T Tauri star. The orbit is rapidly precessing, causing it to stop transiting during part of its orbital evolution. According to Onitsuka et al. (2017), the observations are better explained by a circumstellar dust clump or the occultation of an accretion hotspot.

name: CVSO 30 c
description: CVSO 30 c is a directly imaged candidate companion to the star PTFO 8-8695. It is not yet confirmed whether it is co-moving with the star.

name: Qatar-1 b
description: Qatar-1 b orbits a metal-rich K-dwarf, one of the faintest around which a planet has been discovered by ground based surveys. Measurements of the Rossiter-McLaughlin effect show that the sky-projected obliquity between the orbital plane of the planet and the star's rotation axis is only a few degrees.

name: Qatar-2 b
description: Qatar-2b is a transiting hot Jupiter orbiting a K dwarf and was found by the Qatar Exoplanet Survey (QES). The radial velocity data shows evidence for a second companion with a period of about one year and a mass several times that of Jupiter.

name: Qatar-3 b
description: Data for this planet was imported from the exoplanet.eu database.

name: Qatar-4 b
description: Data for this planet was imported from the exoplanet.eu database.

name: Qatar-5 b
description: Data for this planet was imported from the exoplanet.eu database.

name: Rho Coronae Borealis b
description: The planet candidate orbiting Rho Coronae Borealis was one of the first exoplanet discoveries, with a radial velocity minimum mass of 1.093 Jupiter masses. Subsequent analysis of the Hipparcos astrometric data indicates that the companion is actually a low-mass star in a nearly face-on orbit, however this would make the system unstable.

name: Rho Coronae Borealis c
description: HD 143761 c is a warm Neptune-class planet orbiting external to the previously-known giant planet. For the system to be stable, the inclination cannot be below 4°.

name: Ross 128 b
description: Ross 128 b is a planet with a similar mass to the Earth located near the temperate zone of a nearby red dwarf star. It may be a candidate for being a habitable planet.

name: ROXs 12 b
description: ROXs 12 b is a wide separation planetary mass companion to the star ROXs 12. The object was discovered over 10 years ago in a binary survey program, but follow-up observations only confirmed its planetary nature in 2013.

name: ROXs 42 B b
description: The substellar object ROXs 42B b is orbiting the binary M star ROXs 42B. It is most likely a planet and was discovered in 2013 by Thayne Currie.

name: RR Cae (AB) b
description: The binary RR Cae contains a cool white dwarf and an M-Type dwarf. Eclipse timing variations were used to find a circumbinary planet on an orbit nearly identical to that of Jupiter.

name: SAND364 b
description: The host star of SAND364 b is located in the old open star cluster Messier 67 (M67). There are few galactic clusters which are older and none of those are as close as M67. The survey was conducted by European astronomers. They found that massive planets around stars of open clusters are as frequent as those around field stars.

name: SAND978 b
description: SAND978 is a red giant star in the open cluster M67. A giant planet was discovered orbiting this star in 2017.

name: SDSS J1110+0116
description: Data for this planet was imported from the exoplanet.eu database.

name: SIMP0136+0933
description: Data for this planet was imported from the exoplanet.eu database.

name: Mercury
description: Mercury is the innermost planet in the Solar System.

name: Venus
description: Venus is the second planet from the Sun.

name: Earth
description: Earth is the only known planet able to sustain life.

name: Mars
description: Mars is named after the Roman god of war and often called the red planet.

name: Jupiter
description: Jupiter is two and a half times the mass of all the other planets in the Solar System.

name: Saturn
description: Saturn is best known for its extensive ring system.

name: Uranus
description: Uranus is visible with the naked eye but has never been recognized as a planet by ancient observers.

name: Neptune
description: Neptune is the fourth largest planet in the Solar System.

name: Pluto
description: Pluto is officially categorized as a minor planet by the International Astronomical Union.

name: TAP 26 b
description: Data for this planet was imported from the exoplanet.eu database.

name: tau Boo A b
description: The planet Tau Boötis b was one of the first exoplanets to be discovered back in 1996. In 2012, astronomers have detected the faint glow that is emitted from the planet, reliably probing the structure of the atmosphere of Tau Bootis b and deducing its mass accurately for the first time.

name: tau Ceti b
description: Multiple periodic signals were found by Tuomi et al. in 2012 in the radial velocity data from HARPS, AAPS and HIRES. The planetary nature of the signals has yet to be confirmed.

name: tau Ceti c
description: Multiple periodic signals were found by Tuomi et al. in 2012 in the radial velocity data from HARPS, AAPS and HIRES. The planetary nature of the signals has yet to be confirmed.

name: tau Ceti d
description: Multiple periodic signals were found by Tuomi et al. in 2012 in the radial velocity data from HARPS, AAPS and HIRES. The planetary nature of the signals has yet to be confirmed.

name: tau Ceti e
description: Multiple periodic signals were found by Tuomi et al. in 2012 in the radial velocity data from HARPS, AAPS and HIRES. The planetary nature of the signals has yet to be confirmed.

name: tau Ceti f
description: Multiple periodic signals were found by Tuomi et al. in 2012 in the radial velocity data from HARPS, AAPS and HIRES. The planetary nature of the signals has yet to be confirmed.

name: tau Ceti g
description: Analysis of the Tau Ceti RV data taking into account wavelength-dependent noise indicated a four planet system around the star. Two of the previously-detected planets (e and f) were confirmed, while two new planets were found, designated g and h to avoid confusion with the previous candidates.

name: tau Ceti h
description: Analysis of the Tau Ceti RV data taking into account wavelength-dependent noise indicated a four planet system around the star. Two of the previously-detected planets (e and f) were confirmed, while two new planets were found, designated g and h to avoid confusion with the previous candidates.

name: TCP J05074264+2447555L b
description: The light curve of the microlensing event TCP J05074264+2447555 indicates the lens system contains a 9.2 Earth mass planet orbiting a red dwarf star. The source star is the F dwarf UCAC4 574-013830.

name: TRAPPIST-1 b
description: Astronomers have found this system of seven Earth-sized planets just 40 light-years away. Using ground and space telescopes the planets were all detected as they passed in front of their parent star, the ultracool dwarf star known as TRAPPIST-1. The six inner planets form a near-resonant chain such that their orbital periods (1.51, 2.42, 4.04, 6.06, 9.21, 12.35 days) are near ratios of small integers. This architecture suggests that the planets formed farther from the star and migrated inward. The seven planets have equilibrium temperatures low enough to support liquid water on their surfaces.

name: TrES-2

name: TrES-3 b
description: The planet TrES-3 b has an orbital perdiod of just 31 hours and is undergoing orbital decay due to tidal effects.

name: TrES-5 b

name: Upsilon Andromedae A b
description: The binary star Upsilon Andromedae is only 40 light years away from Earth. The system hosts at least 3 jovian planets. It was the first multiple planet system to be discovered around a main sequence star.

name: UZ For (AB) d
description: UZ Fornacis is an eclipsing polar binary. High-speed photometry and archival eclipse timing data spanning 27 years suggest the presence of extrasolar planets (Potter et al 2011).

name: V391 Peg b

name: V830 Tau b

name: VHS 1256-1257 b
description: VHS 1256-1257 b is a common-proper motion L-dwarf companion of a nearby red dwarf star. It is cooler than expected for a field L-dwarf, and its mass is close to the deuterium-burning limit. The primary was discovered to be a binary of near-equal mass brown dwarfs, there exists a discrepancy between the parallax distance and the spectrophotometric distance to the system.

name: WASP-72 b
description: Despite its extreme irradiation, this planet has a size consistant with that of Jupiter. That makes it a possible outlier among the Hot Jupiters of similar masses, suggesting a significant enrichment in heavy elements.

name: WASP-75 b
description: WASP-75 b is a transiting Hot Jupiter. Its radius is slightly inflated as compared to theoretical planet models with no core.

name: WASP-76 b
description: This hot Jupiter has been discovered by the WASP transit survey and confirmed by radial velocity measurements. It is one of the most irradiated planets known. The host star is evolved and has a post main sequence radius.

name: WASP-77 A b
description: WASP-77 A b is a transiting Hot Jupiter (a planet similar to Jupiter but with an orbit much closer to the host star). It is orbiting a moderately bright G8 V star which is part of a visual binary. The binary has a separation of 3 arcseconds.

name: WASP-78 b
description: WASP-78b is a highly bloated Jupiter-mass exoplanet. It is orbiting an F-type star and was discovered and analyzed using WASP, TRAPPIST and CORALIE data. It is one of the hottest known exoplanets with an equilibrium temperature of 2350 degrees Kelvin.

name: WASP-79 b
description: WASP-79b is a highly bloated Jupiter-mass exoplanet. It is orbiting an F-type star and was discovered and analyzed using WASP, TRAPPIST and CORALIE data. WASP-79b is about twice as big as Jupiter, but its mass is smaller than that of Jupiter.

name: WASP-80 b
description: WASP-80 b is a Jupiter-sized exoplanet but it has only half of Jupiter's mass. It has a transit depth of 3 percent, one of the largest reported so far. The transmission spectrum matches a hazy model with a temperature of 600 K.

name: Wolf 1061 d
description: Wolf 1061 d is a planet with a minimum mass of 5.21 Earth masses located slightly beyond the outer edge of its host star's habitable zone. It is the outermost planet of a system of super-Earths located 14 light years from the solar system.

name: WTS-1 b
description: The Hot Jupiter WTS-1 b is the first extrasolar planet found by the WFCAM Transit Survey. The observations were made at the 3.8-m United Kingdom Infrared Telescope and the Hobby-Eberly Telescope. The planet has one of the largest radius anomalies among the known Hot Jupiters its mass range.

name: WTS-2 b
description: WTS-2 b is an unusually close hot Jupiter on a 1.02-day orbit around a K2V star. The planet is close to the tidal destruction radius of the star and has a predicted remaining lifetime of only 40 million years.

name: xi Aql b
description: xi Aql is a giant star in the constellation of Aquila.

name: XO-2S b
description: The planet XO-2S c is part of a multiplanetary system. The host star itself is part of a binary system. The other binary star, XO-2N also hosts a planet. This configuration makes the system a unique laboratory for understanding the diversity of planetary systems.

name: XO-2S c
description: The planet XO-2S c is part of a multiplanetary system. The host star itself is part of a binary system. The other binary star, XO-2N also hosts a planet. This configuration makes the system a unique laboratory for understanding the diversity of planetary systems.

name: XO-2N b
description: The planet XO-2N b was the first planet discovered in the XO-2 binary. The host star is variable (Zellem et al. 2015) which complicates the analysis of the planetary properties. The stellar variability may be caused by starspots.

name: XO-2N c
description: The radial velocity measurements of the star XO-2 exhibit a long-term quadratic trend. This trend correlates with stellar activity indicators so is more likely due to the stellar activity cycle rather than being caused by reflex motion from a planet.

name: XO-6 b
description: Data for this planet was imported from the exoplanet.eu database.

name: YBP1194 b
description: The star YBP1194 is one of the best solar twins identified so far. Its composition and age is very similar to that of our own Sun. It is located in the star cluster M67 and hosts a 0.33 Jupiter mass planet. The frequency of massive planets around stars of open clusters such as M67 turns out to be very similar to that of field stars.

name: YBP1514 b
description: YBP1514 is a main sequence star in the open star cluster M67. It hosts a 0.4 Jupiter mass planet. The star cluster is between 3.2 and 5 billion years old and contains many stars with ages and compositions similar to that of our own Sun.

name: YBP401 b
description: YBP401 b is a hot Jupiter in an eccentric orbit around an F-type star in the open cluster M67.
